04749nam a22005775i 9780804767637DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222007cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047676377 a10.1515/97808047676372doi  a(DE-B1597)581883  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aPOL0330002bisacsh04aThe Paradox of a Global USA /ced. by Bruce Mazlish, Nayan Chanda, Kenneth Weisbrode. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tForeword -- tContributors -- t1. Introduction -- t2. The Political Structure of a Global World: The Role of the United States -- t3. Globalization as Americanization? -- t4. Expansion and Integration: Reflections on the History of America's Approach to Globalization -- t5. American Exceptionalism and Uneven Global Integration: Resistance to the Global Society -- t6. Crisscrossing the Gods: Globalization and American Religion -- t7. Reverse Flow: European Media in the United States -- t8. Weary Titan, Assertive Hegemon: Military Strategy, Globalization, and U.S. Preponderance -- t9. Globalization and Empire: The Effects of 9/11 and the Iraq War -- t10. Conclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Paradox of a Global USA describes the vexed relationship between the United States and globalization. On the one hand, the U.S. has vociferously promoted modernization and open markets, both central components of the process of globalization. On the other hand, it appears to be resolutely determined not to live within an institutional framework of globalized authority. As the world's only superpower, the United States is often perceived as championing its own narrow national sovereignty—for example, by opposing the Kyoto Protocol and the International Criminal Court, and by taking action in Iraq outside the auspices of the UN. The book treats the paradox of American exceptionalism and globalization as a "local" happening within the broader process of globalization. These essays analyze the ways in which the USA has both played a role in, and reacted against, emerging present-day globalization. Examples are drawn from the fields of history, political science, cultural studies, and economics, making this collection one of the very few to link together so diverse a group of authors and approaches to the subject of global USA.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Globalization.2bisacsh1 aChanda, Nayan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDemerath, N. J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhullar, Nicola Simpson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKurth, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMazlish, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMazlish, Bruce, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPearson, Roberta E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReynolds, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoxborough, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShaw, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTalbott, Strobe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTyrrell, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeisbrode, Kenneth, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 alriye, Akira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uht